A/B Testing - Lesson Notes¶

You need a clear control and clear metrics to run a trustworthy A/B Test.

Process¶

  1. Decide on your change. Changing the color of the 'start now' button from orange to pink.
  2. Form your hypothesis. Changing the 'start now' button from orange to pink will increase how many students explore the courses.
  3. Pick a metric. Total # of courses completed, or # of clicks, click-through-rate (clicks/# of page views), or click-through-probability (unique clicks/unique visitors to page)
  4. Update hypothesis Changing the 'start now' button from orange to pink will increase the click-through-probability of the button.

Rate to measure usability, probability when you want to measure the total impact.

Statistics for A/B Testing¶

Binomial Distribution - A binomial experiment is a statistical experiment that has the following properties: The experiment consists of n repeated trials. Each trial can result in just two possible outcomes. We call one of these outcomes a success and the other, a failure. The probability of success, denoted by P, is the same on every trial.

Confidence Interval - 95% commonly used, this means that if the experiment is repeated over and over you would expect the interval constructed around the sample mean to cover the true value in the population 95% of the time.
